Here's my Round-3 verification against the Round-2 issues:

---

**Q12 BLOCKER (rlimits inconsistency) ‚Äî LOCKED.** The two-mechanism split is now unambiguous. RSS monitoring is always-on, observation-only, never kills anything. Hard `setrlimit` calls happen only when `enforce_rlimits = true` (opt-in, default false). Supervisor self-limit is also opt-in via `enforce_supervisor_rlimit = true`. No overlap, no contradiction.

**Q5 (UUID space) ‚Äî LOCKED.** Explicitly states SHA-256 truncation is rejected ("only 64-bit collision space") and commits to UUID v4 at 122-bit entropy. Router stores the mapping `(slot_uuid, transport_uuid) ‚Üí handler`; adapters never need to know the path shape.

**Q9 (Twilio sig) ‚Äî LOCKED.** The word "HMAC-SHA1 over the URL + sorted POST params (per Twilio spec)" now appears verbatim in the locked text. "Missing/invalid signature ‚Üí 401 + audit log entry (`webhook.invalid_signature`)." Without this, voice webhooks are spoofable ‚Äî the "without this" rationale is present.

**Q10 (Origin allowlist) ‚Äî LOCKED.** "REQUIRED in production. WS upgrade requests with missing or non-allowlisted `Origin` header are rejected with 403 + audit log entry." The rationale is explicit: HMAC cookies alone do not defend against cross-site WebSocket abuse. Empty allowlist = localhost-only dev mode.

**Q11 (OOM budget) ‚Äî LOCKED.** Both subcases documented: (a) code 137 (SIGKILL from OOM killer), (b) code 1 + stderr "MemoryError" (RLIMIT_AS hit, Python catches). The retry-budget-exhaustion assertion is handled by simulating 6 consecutive crashes within 60s ‚Äî a single OOM event does not exhaust the 5-per-minute budget. This is internally consistent with the Q12 rlimits design.

**Q14 (PII clarity) ‚Äî LOCKED.** The three-tier redaction policy is now explicit in the doc. Never logged vs. Logged as identifiers (treated as sensitive but not redacted, required for forensics) vs. `secret.resolve` records only ref name + outcome. The `detail` field treatment is covered: 200-char preview at most for message bodies; full detail only with `--full` flag.

**Q15 (trait shape + graceful shutdown) ‚Äî LOCKED.** `WebhookHandler` trait has `verify` called before `handle` ‚Äî the trait shape forces verify-first. Graceful shutdown: SIGTERM ‚Üí stop accepting new requests ‚Üí drain in-flight HTTP with 30s timeout ‚Üí drop in-flight WS/Twilio sessions with explicit warn log (explicitly notes that waiting for live calls would block shutdown indefinitely). Documented in `http-server-security.md`.

**Transport count wording ‚Äî NEEDS_FIX.** Acceptance criteria item 2 says "7 transport adapters" then enumerates eight comma-separated items: Telegram, Slack Socket, Slack Events, Discord, WhatsApp, Email, Voice, Web. The parenthetical correctly explains Slack ships in two modes as one adapter family, but the leading number 7 is wrong. Goals section gets this right ("5 high-value transports beyond Telegram/Slack = 7 total"). The mismatch is only in AC item 2.

**Phase 13 path ‚Äî CONFIRMED CLEAN.** Phase 13 new code section says "Updated `docs/walkthroughs/multi-transport-subagents.md` covering all 7 transport adapters (Telegram, Slack, Discord, WhatsApp, Email, Voice, Web ‚Äî Slack ships in two modes Socket+Events but is one adapter family)" ‚Äî that's correct. Phase 5b says "This unblocks Phases 7 (WhatsApp), 9 (Voice), 10 (Web)" ‚Äî matches the path.

---

**OVERALL: NEEDS_FIX.** One remaining inconsistency: acceptance criteria item 2 says "7 transport adapters" in the lead but lists 8 in the enumeration. The fix is one word: change "7" to "8" in that item. All other round-2 issues are locked. Once that number is corrected, the doc is clean for round-3 PASS.

